{"cursor":"19323","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" of a mitochondrion showing its mitochondrial matrix and membranes]] The\n 'endosymbiotic theory' postulates that several key organelles of eukaryotes\n originated as symbioses between separate single-celled organisms. According to\n this theory, mitochondria and plastids (e.g. chloroplasts)--and possibly other\n organelles--represent formerly free-living bacteria that were taken inside\n another cell as an endosymbiont. Molecular and biochemical evidence suggest the\n mitochondrion developed from proteobacteria (in particular, Rickettsiales, the\n SAR11 clade, or close relatives) and the chloroplast from\n cyanobacteria.\n","linknr":466,"url":"Endosymbiotic_theory","recorded":1362512556,"links":43,"instances":["biology"],"pdf":["http://www.psychoneuroendocrinology.com/symbiosis.pdf","http://www.psychoneuroendocrinology.com/symbiosis.pdf"],"categories":["Evolutionary biology","Symbiosis"],"headings":["History","From endosymbionts to organelles","Evidence","Secondary endosymbiosis","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/68/Mitochondrion_186.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Endosymbiosis.PNG/300px-Endosymbiosis.PNG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["saltation","biology"]],"members":["saltation"],"related":["Mitochondrion","Organelle","Eukaryote","Symbiosis","Mitochondrion","Plastid","Chloroplast","Bacteria","Endosymbiont","Proteobacteria","Rickettsiales","SAR11_clade","Cyanobacteria","Konstantin_Mereschkowski","Andreas_Franz_Wilhelm_Schimper","Chloroplast","Cyanobacteria","Mitochondrion","Lynn_Margulis","Spirochaete","Flagellum","Cilium","Evolutio